---
export const prerender = true;
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Video Formats Guide — MP4, AVI, MKV, WebM & More" description="Complete guide to video formats — MP4, AVI, MKV, WebM, MOV. Learn codecs, containers, and which format to use when." keywords="video formats, mp4 vs mkv, avi file, video codec, h264, h265, hevc, av1, webm, video compression, video history, container format">
  <div class="max-w-4xl">
    <div class="mb-8">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-2">
        <span class="text-3xl" aria-hidden="true">🎥</span>
        <h1 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white">Video Formats Guide — MP4, AVI, MKV, WebM, MOV</h1>
      </div>
      <p class="text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400">Everything you need to know about video file formats — containers, codecs, history, and the future of moving pictures.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Container vs Codec explainer -->
    <div class="bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 rounded-xl border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 p-5 mb-8">
      <h2 class="text-sm font-semibold text-amber-800 dark:text-amber-300 mb-2">💡 Container vs Codec — What's the Difference?</h2>
      <p class="text-sm text-amber-700 dark:text-amber-400">A <strong>container</strong> (MP4, MKV, AVI) is the "box" that holds the data. A <strong>codec</strong> (H.264, H.265, AV1) is the compression algorithm that encodes/decodes the video stream inside. Think of a container as a lunchbox and the codec as the recipe used to prepare the food inside.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Format comparison table -->
    <div class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 p-6 mb-8 shadow-sm overflow-x-auto">
      <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-4">Container Formats</h2>
      <table class="w-full text-sm text-left">
        <thead>
          <tr class="border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700">
            <th class="px-3 py-2 font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Format</th>
            <th class="px-3 py-2 font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Year</th>
            <th class="px-3 py-2 font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Creator</th>
            <th class="px-3 py-2 font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Codecs Supported</th>
            <th class="px-3 py-2 font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Best For</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          <tr class="border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5 font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">MP4 (.mp4)</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">2001</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">ISO/MPEG</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">H.264, H.265, AAC</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">Universal playback, web, mobile</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5 font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">AVI (.avi)</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">1992</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">Microsoft</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">DivX, Xvid, MPEG-4</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">Legacy Windows systems</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5 font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">MKV (.mkv)</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">2002</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">Matroska.org</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">Nearly all codecs</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">High-quality archival, subtitles</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5 font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">WebM (.webm)</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">2010</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">Google</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">VP8, VP9, AV1</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">Web streaming, royalty-free</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5 font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">MOV (.mov)</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">1991</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">Apple</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">H.264, ProRes, HEVC</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">Apple ecosystem, pro editing</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5 font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">WMV (.wmv)</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">1999</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">Microsoft</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">WMV9, VC-1</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">Windows Media Player, DRM</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <!-- Codec comparison -->
    <div class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 p-6 mb-8 shadow-sm overflow-x-auto">
      <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-4">Video Codecs</h2>
      <table class="w-full text-sm text-left">
        <thead>
          <tr class="border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700">
            <th class="px-3 py-2 font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Codec</th>
            <th class="px-3 py-2 font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Year</th>
            <th class="px-3 py-2 font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Efficiency vs H.264</th>
            <th class="px-3 py-2 font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Royalty-Free?</th>
            <th class="px-3 py-2 font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Notes</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          <tr class="border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5 font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">H.264 (AVC)</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">2003</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">Baseline</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5"><span class="text-red-500">No</span></td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">Still the most compatible codec worldwide</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5 font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">H.265 (HEVC)</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">2013</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">~50% smaller</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5"><span class="text-red-500">No</span></td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">4K streaming standard, complex licensing</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5 font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">VP9</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">2013</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">~40% smaller</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5"><span class="text-green-500">Yes</span></td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">YouTube's primary codec for HD/4K</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5 font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">AV1</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">2018</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">~50-60% smaller</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5"><span class="text-green-500">Yes</span></td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">Future standard — Netflix, YouTube adopting</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5 font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">VVC (H.266)</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">2020</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">~50% smaller than HEVC</td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5"><span class="text-red-500">No</span></td>
            <td class="px-3 py-2.5">Targeting 8K and 360° video</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <!-- History timeline -->
    <div class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 p-6 mb-8 shadow-sm">
      <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-5">A Brief History of Video</h2>
      <div class="space-y-4">
        <div class="flex gap-4">
          <div class="w-16 text-xs font-bold text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 shrink-0 pt-0.5">1888</div>
          <div>
            <p class="text-sm font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">Roundhay Garden Scene</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400">The oldest surviving motion picture. Filmed by Louis Le Prince in Leeds, England — it lasts just 2.11 seconds and shows people walking in a garden. Le Prince mysteriously vanished two years later on a train.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="flex gap-4">
          <div class="w-16 text-xs font-bold text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 shrink-0 pt-0.5">1956</div>
          <div>
            <p class="text-sm font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">First Video Tape Recorder</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400">Ampex's VRX-1000 cost $50,000 and used 2-inch reels spinning at 15,000 RPM. CBS broadcast the first pre-recorded TV show using it. A single reel held just 90 minutes and weighed 30 pounds.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="flex gap-4">
          <div class="w-16 text-xs font-bold text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 shrink-0 pt-0.5">1976</div>
          <div>
            <p class="text-sm font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">VHS vs Betamax</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400">JVC's VHS launched against Sony's Betamax in one of tech's most famous format wars. Betamax had better picture quality but VHS offered longer recording time (2 hours vs 1 hour). VHS won through licensing to more manufacturers.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="flex gap-4">
          <div class="w-16 text-xs font-bold text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 shrink-0 pt-0.5">1995</div>
          <div>
            <p class="text-sm font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">DVD Arrives</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400">The DVD delivered 480p video with 4.7 GB capacity — 7× more than a CD. Unlike VHS/Betamax, competing companies (Sony, Philips, Toshiba, Panasonic) agreed on a single standard. The first DVD player cost $1,000.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="flex gap-4">
          <div class="w-16 text-xs font-bold text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 shrink-0 pt-0.5">2005</div>
          <div>
            <p class="text-sm font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">YouTube Launches</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400">The first video uploaded was "Me at the zoo" — 18 seconds of co-founder Jawed Karim at the San Diego Zoo. Today YouTube hosts over 800 million videos and delivers over 1 billion hours of watch time daily.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="flex gap-4">
          <div class="w-16 text-xs font-bold text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 shrink-0 pt-0.5">2018</div>
          <div>
            <p class="text-sm font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">AV1 Released</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400">The Alliance for Open Media (Google, Mozilla, Cisco, Netflix, Amazon, Apple, Microsoft) released AV1 as a royalty-free codec to break the patent stranglehold of H.265/HEVC. It's 30% more efficient than VP9.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Interesting facts -->
    <div class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 p-6 mb-8 shadow-sm">
      <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-4">🎬 Fascinating Video Facts</h2>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800 rounded-lg">
          <p class="text-sm font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-1">Internet Traffic Dominance</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400">Video accounts for over 82% of all internet traffic in 2024. A single hour of 4K Netflix streaming consumes about 7 GB. Without modern compression codecs, the internet would collapse under the weight of uncompressed video.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800 rounded-lg">
          <p class="text-sm font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-1">Uncompressed 4K Reality</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400">One second of uncompressed 4K video at 60fps requires 1.5 GB of storage. A 2-hour movie would need 10.8 TB. H.265 compresses this by roughly 1000:1 while maintaining perceptual quality — a genuine marvel of engineering.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800 rounded-lg">
          <p class="text-sm font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-1">The $1.5 Billion Patent Pool</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400">H.265/HEVC has three competing patent pools with over 10,000 claimed patents. The licensing complexity is so extreme that it directly motivated the creation of AV1 as a royalty-free alternative. Some companies face licensing fees exceeding $1/device.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800 rounded-lg">
          <p class="text-sm font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-1">YouTube's Encoding Farm</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400">Every minute, 500 hours of video are uploaded to YouTube. Each video is transcoded into 20+ different resolution/codec combinations. YouTube's encoding infrastructure processes more video in a single day than the entire film industry produced in its first 100 years.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800 rounded-lg">
          <p class="text-sm font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-1">The MKV Revolution</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400">Matroska (MKV) was named after Russian nesting dolls because it can contain virtually unlimited streams — video, audio, subtitles, chapters, attachments — all in one file. It's open-source and has become the archivists' container of choice.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800 rounded-lg">
          <p class="text-sm font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-1">Frame Rate Perception</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400">Cinema uses 24fps because it was the minimum that saved film stock while avoiding flicker. Peter Jackson's "The Hobbit" at 48fps divided audiences — some found it "too real," calling it the "soap opera effect." Games target 60-120fps for responsiveness.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Present challenges & future -->
    <div class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 p-6 shadow-sm">
      <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-4">Present Challenges & Future Prospects</h2>
      <div class="space-y-4 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-1">8K and Beyond</h3>
          <p>8K (7680×4320) offers 33 million pixels per frame — four times 4K. Japan's NHK broadcast the 2024 Olympics in 8K. The challenge: encoding 8K in real-time requires enormous compute, and most viewers sit too far from their screens to perceive the difference from 4K.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-1">AI-Powered Video Compression</h3>
          <p>Neural video codecs from companies like WaveOne (acquired by Apple) and Deep Render use machine learning to understand scene content, achieving better compression than traditional codecs. They can "hallucinate" detail during decompression, raising questions about what counts as authentic video.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-1">Volumetric Video & Light Fields</h3>
          <p>The next frontier is capturing full 3D scenes viewable from any angle — "video holograms." Companies like Leia and Looking Glass are building displays. The data rates are staggering: a single frame of volumetric video can exceed 1 GB. No existing codec is designed for this.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-1">Environmental Impact</h3>
          <p>Video streaming's carbon footprint is substantial — estimated at 300 million tonnes of CO2 per year. More efficient codecs like AV1 could reduce this significantly by requiring less bandwidth. The EU has considered mandating codec efficiency standards for streaming services.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Suggest a feature -->
    <div class="mt-6 text-center">
      <a href="/suggest?title=Video+Formats+Guide" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 text-sm text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 hover:underline font-medium">
        <span aria-hidden="true">💡</span> Suggest a new feature for this tool →
      </a>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
